anish libraries, Byrne shows that Spanish writers such as Miguel de Cervantes, Lope de Vega, Bartolomé de las Casas, and Garcilaso de la Vega all responded to Ficino and adapted his imagery for their own works. An important contribution to the study of Spanish literature and culture from the fifteenth to the seventeenth centuries, Ficino in Spain recovers the role that Hermetic and Neoplatonic thought played in the world of Spanish literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aHermetism in literaturexHistoryx16th century. 0aHermetism in literaturexHistoryy16th century. 0aNeoplatonism in literaturexHistoryx16th century. 0aNeoplatonism in literaturexHistoryy16th century. 0aRenaissancexSpain. 0aRenaissancezSpain. 0aSpanish literaturexHistory and criticismxClassical period, 1500-1700. 0aSpanish literatureyClassical period, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144262407840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442624078423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442624078.jpg  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles